# When Blocking Fails: A Study in Identifying the Real Bottleneck

## Initial Assumption

After observing that the `IKJ` loop ordering significantly outperformed the other five loop permutations, the next logical optimization appeared to be **cache blocking (tiling)**.

The hypothesis was:

> Since blocking is widely used in high-performance matrix multiplication libraries, applying blocking to the already cache-friendly IKJ algorithm should produce an additional speedup.

However, the experiments revealed something unexpected.

---

## Experimental Setup

### Baseline Algorithm (Naive IKJ)

```c
for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
    for (int k = 0; k < N; k++) {

        int r = A[i][k];

        for (int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
            C[i][j] += r * B[k][j];
        }
    }
}
```

Characteristics:

* Row-major memory layout.
* Register reuse through `r`.
* Sequential traversal of B.
* Sequential traversal of C.

Matrix Size:

```text
N = 4096
```

Measured Time:

```text
56.61 seconds
```

---

## Blocked Implementation

The blocked version used:

```c
for(ii)
    for(kk)
        for(jj)
            for(i)
                for(k)
                    for(j)
```

with varying block sizes.

---

## Results

| Block Size | Execution Time |
| ---------: | -------------: |
|          4 |       113.67 s |
|          8 |       101.90 s |
|         16 |        92.68 s |
|         32 |        86.96 s |
|         64 |        85.04 s |
|        128 |        84.80 s |

Baseline IKJ:

| Method    |        Time |
| --------- | ----------: |
| Naive IKJ | **56.61 s** |

---

## First Observation

Increasing block size consistently improved the blocked implementation:

```text
113 s
↓
102 s
↓
93 s
↓
87 s
↓
85 s
↓
85 s
```

This suggests that:

> Smaller tiles suffer from excessive loop overhead.

The blocked algorithm introduces three additional loops:

```text
ii
kk
jj
```

resulting in six nested loops instead of three.

This causes:

* More branch evaluations,
* More index arithmetic,
* More loop-control instructions.

For small block sizes, the overhead dominates.

---

## Second Observation

The improvement eventually saturated:

```text
BS = 32 → 86.96 s
BS = 64 → 85.04 s
BS = 128 → 84.80 s
```

Beyond a certain point, increasing block size provided almost no additional benefit.

This indicates:

> The blocked implementation had already extracted whatever locality improvement it could offer.

---

## The Unexpected Result

Even the best blocked implementation remained significantly slower than the naive IKJ version.

Best blocked result:

```text
84.80 s
```

Naive IKJ:

```text
56.61 s
```

Ratio:

```text
84.80 / 56.61 ≈ 1.50× slower
```

---

# Why Did Blocking Fail?

The answer lies in the baseline algorithm itself.

The naive IKJ implementation already exhibited excellent locality.

---

## Matrix A

```text
A[i][k]
```

loaded once:

```c
int r = A[i][k];
```

and reused across the entire inner loop.

This maximized register reuse.

---

## Matrix B

Access pattern:

```text
B[k][0]
B[k][1]
B[k][2]
...
```

which corresponds to sequential row traversal in row-major storage.

---

## Matrix C

Updated as:

```text
C[i][0]
C[i][1]
C[i][2]
...
```

also sequential.

---

## Hardware Prefetchers

The CPU observes a smooth memory stream:

```text
→→→→→→→→→→→→
```

and begins fetching future cache lines before they are requested.

Effectively:

> The hardware was already performing part of the optimization automatically.

---

# What Blocking Changed

Blocking transformed the access pattern from:

```text
Long continuous streams
```

into:

```text
Small chunks
↓
Jump
↓
Small chunks
↓
Jump
```

Consequences:

* Reduced effectiveness of hardware prefetching,
* Additional loop overhead,
* Increased branch instructions.

Thus:

```text
Blocking Overhead
>
Blocking Benefit
```

for this particular algorithm and architecture.

---

# The Core Insight

This experiment demonstrates a fundamental principle of performance engineering:

> Optimizations only help when they target an actual bottleneck.

The IKJ algorithm had already addressed the major locality issue.

Blocking attempted to solve a problem that no longer significantly existed.

---

# Why Blocking Still Matters

This does **not** mean blocking is useless.

Blocking becomes valuable when:

### 1. Poor Loop Orders

For example:

```text
IJK
```

which traverses columns of B.

Blocking can dramatically improve locality.

---

### 2. Multi-Core Execution

Tiles become natural units of work for thread scheduling.

---

### 3. Register-Level Microkernels

Modern BLAS implementations use multiple layers of blocking:

```text
L3 blocking
↓
L2 blocking
↓
L1 blocking
↓
Register blocking
```

to exploit every level of the memory hierarchy.

---

# Final Conclusion

The expectation was:

```text
IKJ
↓
Blocking
↓
Faster execution
```

The experiments instead showed:

```text
IKJ
↓
Hardware already exploits locality
↓
Blocking introduces overhead
↓
Slower execution
```

This result highlights an important lesson:

> The existence of an optimization in textbooks does not guarantee that it improves performance in every context.

True high-performance computing requires identifying the actual bottleneck before applying optimizations.

Sometimes, the simplest algorithm aligned with the hardware is already the best solution.
